<item>
            <title>[SPARK-2498] Concurrent initialization of various DataType objects causes exceptions</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/SPARK-2498</link>
                <project id="12315420" key="SPARK">Spark</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;Reported by Keith Simmons and gorenuru &lt;a href=&quot;http://apache-spark-user-list.1001560.n3.nabble.com/Error-while-running-Spark-SQL-join-when-using-Spark-1-0-1-td9776.html&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;. This is probably due to the fact that Scala Reflection API is not thread-safe for 2.10.* versions; see &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.scala-lang.org/browse/SI-6240&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;SI-6240&lt;/a&gt; for more details.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The purposed fix is to add a lock object that is synchronized on when various data type objects make use of the reflection API (during their initializations or other places in program execution). (Longer-term, we could consider evolving this to a SparkSQL-global lock, and all calls to the reflection APi from Spark SQL should probably synchronize on it.)&lt;/p&gt;</description>
